---

<ProjectLayout title="MCU Design" activeSlug="mcu">
  <h2>Overview</h2>
  <p>
    The STM32L432KC serves as the front-end data acquisition system. Using a hardware timer-triggered ADC
    with double buffering, it samples analog audio, converts to digital, and transmits data packets to the
    FPGA via SPI. After peripheral setup, the MCU operates in two states: idle and sampling — toggled by
    a button press.
  </p>

  <h2>Data Acquisition Architecture</h2>

  <h3>ADC Initialization &amp; Interrupts</h3>
  <p>
    The ADC runs in non-continuous mode, triggered externally by TIM6. Continuous mode makes it hard to
    ensure constant sample spacing; using a timer gives precise control over the sampling rate.
  </p>
  <p>
    TIM6 triggers at 5kHz (<code>EXTSEL = 13</code>, rising-edge trigger). Sampling rate is chosen by
    balancing three factors:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>FFT resolution</strong> = Sampling Rate / FFT Size — higher rate reduces frequency resolution</li>
    <li><strong>Nyquist limit</strong> — max detectable frequency = Fs / 2; high C (C6) ≈ 1046Hz</li>
    <li><strong>Data points per period</strong> — more samples per note improves accuracy</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    ADC resolution is set to 8-bit (not the standard 12-bit) because: (1) math logic complexity scales
    with bit depth on the FPGA; (2) 8-bit data fits cleanly into one SPI transmission.
  </p>

  <h3>Double Buffering</h3>
  <p>
    To prevent data loss during SPI transmission, two 512-byte buffers (<code>buffer0</code>, <code>buffer1</code>)
    are used. <code>fillBuffer</code> points to the array being written by the ADC; <code>sendBuffer</code>
    points to the stable array ready for SPI. When the ADC fills <code>fillBuffer</code>, the interrupt handler
    swaps pointers and raises a <code>bufferReady</code> flag. The main loop detects this and begins
    transmitting while the ADC writes to the new <code>fillBuffer</code>.
  </p>
  <p>
    DMA was not used — CPU overhead for 5kHz interrupts is negligible, and standard interrupts allow
    simpler, explicit control over pointer swapping and easier real-time debugging via GPIO toggles.
  </p>

  <h2>SPI Communication</h2>
  <p>
    The MCU acts as SPI Master. The Chip Select (CS) line is toggled manually for every byte to provide
    a clear signal for each sample received by the FPGA.
  </p>
